        {
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 1,
          "text": "Theories Of Failure :"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "1) Rankine Theory (Maximum Stress theory/Maximum normal stress)"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Max$^m$ stress $(\\sigma_1 \\text{ or } \\sigma_3 \\text{ whenever is maximum}) = \\sigma_y \\text{ yield}"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Avoid failure"
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\sigma_1 = \\frac{\\sigma_y}{\\text{FOS}} \\text{ (max)}",
          "display": true
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Failure in cylinders occurs at a point when maximum principle stress / normal stress in a biaxial stress system reaches the maximum limiting value of material strength in a simple test."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "(2) Guest's Theory or Coulomb's theory or Maximum shear theory"
        },
        {
          "type": "math",
          "latex": "\\left( \\sigma_1 - \\sigma_2 \\right) \\text{ or } \\left( \\sigma_2 - \\sigma_3 \\right) \\text{ or } \\left( \\sigma_3 - \\sigma_1 \\right) \\left( \\text{whichever is maximum} \\right) = \\sigma_y",
          "display": true
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Failure on yielding occurs at a point in members when maximum shear in a biaxial stress system reaches the limiting value of shear in a simple tension test."
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "* Above theorem is applicable to Ductile material."
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
